MUI (formerly Material UI) is a comprehensive React UI library providing a set of pre-built, customizable components that implement Google's Material Design. It offers a wide range of tools and components for building consistent and visually appealing user interfaces in React applications.

Use MUI when you're building React applications and want to leverage a well-established design system with a large community and extensive documentation. It's suitable for projects that benefit from a consistent, Material Design-inspired look and feel.

Avoid MUI if you're not using React, or if you need a design that significantly deviates from Material Design. Also, consider the relatively large bundle size and the potential performance implications of using a large component library.
MUI has 51 components, 32 of them are unique â€“ for example pagination and button group are considered as same.
Does not support more than 2 themes at the same time

MUI has 85 third-party dependencies. Using more third-party dependencies increases the risk of security vulnerabilities, compatibility problems, and long-term maintenance headaches from deprecated packages.
MUI CSS file is not available on CDN
MUI does not use semantic CSS class names. Using semantic and descriptive CSS class names improves readability and maintainability of code independent of the current framework.
MUI requires changing JavaScript props one by one at build time to do design token customization
MUI does not provide micro CSS files for each component
MUI does not use wide-gamut P3 colors by default
MUI customizations requires changing styles at build time
MUI doesn not use native CSS nesting

Preline UI is an open-source set of prebuilt UI components based on the utility-first CSS framework, Tailwind CSS. It offers a range of customizable components and interactive elements designed to accelerate web development.

Use Preline UI when you want to quickly build web interfaces with Tailwind CSS and need a set of pre-designed components to speed up the development process. It's suitable for projects where you want to leverage the flexibility of Tailwind CSS with ready-to-use UI elements.

Avoid Preline UI if you require a component library with extensive built-in theming capabilities or highly customized designs that deviate significantly from the default Preline UI styles. Also, be mindful of the dependency size and potential maintenance overhead associated with third-party dependencies.
Preline is framework agnostic and works everywhere
Preline has 77 Components, 66 of them are unique â€“ for example pagination and button group are considered as same.
Preline has light and dark themes
Preline CSS file is available on CDN
Preline does not use semantic CSS class names. Using semantic and descriptive CSS class names improves readability and maintainability of code independent of the current framework.
Preline requires changing class names one by one at build time to do customization
Preline does not provide micro CSS files for each component
Preline uses wide-gamut P3 colors by default
Preline customizations requires changing Tailwind CSS class names at build time
Preline doesn not use native CSS nesting
